<TITLE> India holds ceasefire talks with Naga rebels </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 GUWAHATI, India, July 31 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Talks to extend a ceasefire for India's longest-running insurgency in the remote northeastern state of Nagaland began on Tuesday with the main separatist rebel group demanding firm peace proposals from India. The Naga insurgency is aimed at creating a separate state of "Greater Nagaland" for ethnic Naga people of the region. Since it began in 1947, about 20,000 people have died in the conflict. A ceasefire between the National Socialist Council of Nagaland (Issac-Muivah), or NSCN (I-M), and Indian security forces has held since 1997 with periodical extensions. The current ceasefire ends on Tuesday and is up for review during the talks between rebel leaders and Indian officials. "This time we want to see the government of India come up with some concrete proposals to solve the Naga problem otherwise, by extending ceasefire, no tangible results are expected," a senior rebel leader, who asked to remain anonymous, told Reuters by telephone. The demand for the creation of "Greater Nagaland" from the Naga-dominated areas of neighbouring states has been ruled out by India which says other ethnic people living in adjacent provinces are not ready to part with any territory. Security analysts say peace with the Nagas is crucial to a broader peace in the oil- and tea-rich northeast. This is the first time the peace talks are being held in Nagaland. Earlier talks took place in New Delhi and abro
